    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.15"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">15</fw>
                
                <fw type="imprint">
                    <figure>
                        <figDesc>Pocket Books Logo: A Kangaroo Reading a Book</figDesc>
                    </figure> 
                    
                    <hi rend="italics"><hi rend="caps">POCKET BOOKS</hi> 
                        <lb/>
                    A Division of Simon &amp; Schuster, Inc. 
                        <lb/>
                    Rockefeller Center, 630 Fifth Avenue 
                        <lb/>
                    New York, <hi rend="caps">N.Y.</hi> 10020
                        <lb/>
                    Telephone 212 Circle 5-6400</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>June 16, 1972</dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>5835 Vine Street</addrLine> 
                        <addrLine>Lincoln, Nebraska</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you for your letter. You have no idea how proud we are that <hi rend="caps">BLACK ELK SPEAKS</hi> is a Pocket Book. It is certainly one of those very few books which will live. The surprising and pleasing thing is how many people have discovered it already.</p>
                
                <p>Since publication we have received orders for over 160,000 copies and last week alone there were orders for 9,000 books. Last week I saw the re-run of the Dick Cavett Show which was very moving and memorable. It will certainly have a strong effect on the book.</p>
                
                <p>The 25 copies you need are being sent to you from our warehouse in Buffalo, and I will send 10 copies to Vina Bind if you will let me know the address. Don't worry about payment for either of these shipments. They can be charged to your future royalities or may be considered as promotional copies which we will pay for here.</p>
                
                <p>I look forward to reading your autobiography when it is ready at Harcourt Brace, and hope that someday we may have a chance to meet.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>With all best wishes,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Bernard Shir-Cliff</signed>
                    <signed>Bernard W. Shir-Cliff
                    Executive Editor</signed> 
                
                    <note>BWS:jb</note> 
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
